courses.learning_outcomes:
Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) understand the meaning and basic characteristics of risk and insurance;
(2) appreciate the major methods of handling risk, including risk control techniques and risk financing techniques;
(3) understand the law of large numbers and its application to insurance;
(4) explain the legal principle of insurance;
(5) acquire basic knowledge of financial and insurance products; and
(6) understand the basic components of financial risk management, namely market risk, credit risk and operational risk management.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) understand the risk management topics covered in the source material;
(2) speak about and present clearly (in English) the topics covered;
(3) participate in discussions with others about sophisticated risk management topics; and
(4) prepare questions for presenters, just as in seminars.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand the basic financial derivatives and their pricing;
(2) learn the simulation of stochastic processes, in particular Ito’s processes;
(3) learn the application of Ito’s lemma in simulation;
(4) understand value at risk for measuring market risk;
(5) acquire programming skills in EXCEL VBA; and

(6) use variance reduction to enhance simulation quality.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) understand the basic notion of copulas and perform simulations according to the Black-Scholes model that facilitates for financial data cleansing;
(2) grasp the idea of using GARCH to model the evolutions of volatilities and correlations;
(3) calibrate various risk measures with the use of Extreme Value Theory;
(4) use principal component analysis and canonical correlation analysis and understand its connection with simple recommender systems and its applications in term-structures of interest rates;
(5) carry out cluster analysis with various machine learning tools such as perceptrons, classification trees, k-means clustering algorithm, Bayes classifiers;
(6) grasp the concept of ANN and logit regression for categorical data analysis;
(7) analyse real data using suitable proper techniques from both statistics and machine learning and write reports to summarise findings;
(8) understand how to consider problems from different perspectives, particularly related to those in finance and risk management science, and analyse quantitative evidence in a critical manner.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) explain the notion of variation as a measure of risk and its relationship to statistics and risk management;
(2) demonstrate the ability to understand the concepts of mean-variance analysis and Markowitz optimal portfolio for a one-period investment;
(3) interpret and infer from the mean-variance analysis and the ideas of efficient frontiers and minimum variance portfolio;
(4) understand the notion of factor models and their relationships to linear regressions;
(5) relate the celebrated CAPM model with factor models and their statistical underpinnings;
(6) explain the concepts of APT and its reconciliation with the CAPM;
(7) explain and demonstrate the basic notions of diffusions and their applications to finance and risk management;
(8) demonstrate a basic understanding of Ito’s calculus;
(9) demonstrate a working knowledge of applying Ito’s calculus, in particular with respect to standard Brownian motion;
(10) differentiate both conceptually and practically the notion of integration by parts between ordinary and Ito’s calculus;
(11) apply Ito’s calculus to option pricing and the Black-Scholes formula; and

(12) acquire the necessary background for other courses in risk management and finance, including but not limited to RMSC4001, RMSC4002, RMSC4005 and RMSC4007.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand, in an actuarial context, what is meant by the word “model”, how and why models are used, their advantages and their limitations;
(2) understand the important results that can be obtained from these models for the purpose of making business decisions and the approaches that can be used to determine these results;
(3) generalise knowledge from the actuarial sector to other business environments; and

(4) solve the questions in Exams M and C offered by the Society of Actuaries.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to

(1) understand derivative pricing theories;
(2) understand structure products and their risk management;
(3) conduct risk management reports of financial products;
(4) enhance their teamwork and presentation skills; and

(5) understand structural credit risk models.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) understand and appreciate various cutting-edges techniques in Risk Management and Statistics;
(2) apply a scientific mindset of constant skepticism in formulating and tackling real problems;
(3) master advanced concepts of risk analytics;
(4) combine and utilize various methods in Statistics and Computer Science learnt in different courses;
(5) enhance ability to work in teams.

Upon completion of the course, students should be able to
(1) understand and get a taste of the real risk management business;
(2) learn communication skills among business collaborators;
(3) learn practical quantitative skills for risk management;
(4) conduct research on practical financial and risk management problems; and
(5) learn presentation skills.

